    {"instruction": "What is the most important card slot in a Legacy deck?", "input": "", "output": "The 1-mana spell slot. Legacy is defined by 1-mana spells: Brainstorm, Ponder, Thoughtseize, Swords to Plowshares, Lightning Bolt, Daze (free but MV 1), Delver of Secrets, Dark Ritual, Goblin Lackey, Mother of Runes, Aether Vial. Every competitive deck maximizes its 1-mana plays. If your deck's best turn-1 play is passing with a land, you are probably too slow for Legacy. The exception is prison decks that use 0-mana acceleration (Ancient Tomb, Lotus Petal) to deploy 2-3 mana lock pieces on turn 1 instead."},
    {"instruction": "How do I know if my Legacy deck is good?", "input": "", "output": "Test against the tier 1 metagame: 1) Does it have a positive win rate against Dimir Tempo (14.6%)? If not, you lose your most common matchup. 2) Does it have a plan against fast combo (Oops, Storm)? If not, you get turn-1/2 killed. 3) Does it function through Chalice of the Void on 1? If not, prison decks destroy you. 4) Can it win by turn 5-6 against a goldfish? If not, you are too slow. 5) Is every card in your deck the most efficient version of its effect? If you are playing 2+ mana cards that could be 1-mana alternatives, replace them. A Legacy deck that passes all 5 tests is competitive."},
    {"instruction": "What is wrong with playing more than 60 cards in Legacy?", "input": "", "output": "Every card above 60 reduces your probability of drawing your best cards. If your best card is a 4-of in 60 cards, you see it in about 40% of opening hands. In 65 cards, that drops to 37%. In 80 cards (Yorion), it drops to 32%. Legacy rewards consistency because matchups are diverse and you need specific answers. The only exception is Yorion companion (80 cards), where the guaranteed companion value compensates for reduced consistency. Even then, Yorion builds accept lower consistency as a trade-off."},
    {"instruction": "When should I splash a third color in my Legacy deck?", "input": "", "output": "Splash a third color only when: 1) The splashed cards are worth the mana base damage (Uro in Bant Control, Pyroblast in Grixis). 2) You can support it with 1-2 dual lands and fetchlands that already serve your main colors. 3) The splash does not weaken your Blood Moon resilience (more nonbasics = more vulnerability). 4) You have enough cantrips to find the splash color when needed. Bad reasons to splash: adding a marginally better removal spell, or a creature that is only slightly better than alternatives in your main colors. The deckbuilding cost of a splash (life from fetching, Wasteland vulnerability, Blood Moon risk) must be outweighed by the power gain."},
